00:10:09.310 --> 00:10:11.510
Why a book festival?

00:10:11.510 --> 00:10:14.530
Why you? Juneteenth?

00:10:14.530 --> 00:10:16.660
Book festival, for real?

00:10:16.660 --> 00:10:19.540
So first of all, I'm an immigrant.

00:10:19.540 --> 00:10:20.840
I was born in London.

00:10:20.840 --> 00:10:22.770
I came over as a young child.

00:10:22.770 --> 00:10:27.220
And so I don't have the
African-American story.

00:10:27.220 --> 00:10:30.170
I have the African story.

00:10:30.170 --> 00:10:34.680
And the beauty of the African
story and the African diaspora is

00:10:34.680 --> 00:10:43.630
that waters, borders,
governments set lines and this is

00:10:43.630 --> 00:10:45.230
where this one begins and this is

00:10:45.230 --> 00:10:48.810
where that one ends means
nothing to the African people.

00:10:48.810 --> 00:10:51.970
You know your people, right?

00:10:51.970 --> 00:10:56.830
And so for me, being
able to say, "Okay,

00:10:56.830 --> 00:11:03.710
I want to put together something
that celebrates the thing

00:11:03.710 --> 00:11:07.430
that I love which is words, the
thing that was given to me early

00:11:07.430 --> 00:11:08.730
on in life which is words.

00:11:08.730 --> 00:11:10.920
Whereas we didn't have a lot
of money, we didn't have a lot

00:11:10.920 --> 00:11:14.490
of access to a lot of things but
we had access to the libraries.

00:11:14.490 --> 00:11:19.060
Libraries at school, libraries
at home and we made use of them."

00:11:19.060 --> 00:11:22.700
So when things happen that were
as wonderful, I went to a book.

00:11:22.700 --> 00:11:27.660 position:56%
When things -- something happened
that was horrible, I went to a book.

00:11:27.660 --> 00:11:33.130
And that's exactly what
they were doing back 1865 --

00:11:33.130 --> 00:11:40.770
1773, Phyllis Whitley was
writing when it was uncalled for.

00:11:40.770 --> 00:11:42.820
She was supposed to just survive.

00:11:42.820 --> 00:11:46.390
How dare she sit back and create?

00:11:46.390 --> 00:11:51.280
How dare she take the word and make
it her own, form her own sentences,

00:11:51.280 --> 00:11:54.930
create her own thoughts,
write her own story?

00:11:54.930 --> 00:11:57.410
Write her own story.

00:11:57.410 --> 00:12:02.060
That is what I want us to remember
is to write our own stories.

00:12:02.060 --> 00:12:05.960
Be stewards of our stories.

00:12:05.960 --> 00:12:09.490
One of the things that makes
a person free is the ability

00:12:09.490 --> 00:12:12.450
to define and think for yourself.

00:12:12.450 --> 00:12:16.820 position:56%
There's a reason why we're doing
this here in the Library of Congress

00:12:16.820 --> 00:12:20.900
because this is the land of
the primary source, people.

00:12:20.900 --> 00:12:25.730 position:56%
You don't have to go to another
source to have something fed to you.

00:12:25.730 --> 00:12:27.030
You can go to the source.

00:12:27.030 --> 00:12:31.050
It is open and available to you
and find out and write about it

00:12:31.050 --> 00:12:35.040
and critique it for yourself.

00:12:36.910 --> 00:12:43.940
Juneteenth is about, yes, Galveston
and the emancipations and it's kind

00:12:43.940 --> 00:12:49.340
of story but the history of
emancipation is a storied history.

00:12:49.340 --> 00:12:52.940
There are, we have
emancipation Day on April 16th

00:12:52.940 --> 00:12:56.730
in DC then you have Juneteenth
on June 19th and people kind

00:12:56.730 --> 00:12:58.030
of throw their hands up in the air

00:12:58.030 --> 00:12:59.570
because they don't
really know what it is

00:12:59.570 --> 00:13:03.540
because that's exactly
how it unfolded.

00:13:03.540 --> 00:13:05.420
It was storied.

00:13:05.420 --> 00:13:09.710
It was complicated and then
the story was retold in ways

00:13:09.710 --> 00:13:14.670
