Freedom War Foundation and Museum.

00:14:37.550 --> 00:14:39.000
All right.

00:14:47.370 --> 00:14:48.710
&gt;&gt; Hari Jones: Good morning.

00:14:48.710 --> 00:14:50.650
&gt;&gt; Good morning.

00:14:50.650 --> 00:14:56.830
&gt;&gt; Hari Jones: Today, I will
begin by telling you a lie.

00:14:58.110 --> 00:15:07.970
That lie is that on June 19, 1865,
slaves in Texas finally learned

00:15:07.970 --> 00:15:09.270
that they had been freed

00:15:09.270 --> 00:15:15.290
by the Emancipation
Proclamation on January 1, 1863.

00:15:15.290 --> 00:15:22.850
This lie has been advanced in
legislation, in the popular culture

00:15:22.850 --> 00:15:27.250
as an explanation for
Juneteenth celebrations.

00:15:27.250 --> 00:15:32.940
This lie is predicated on a
fundamental misunderstanding

00:15:32.940 --> 00:15:38.610
of the Emancipation
Proclamation and its enforcement.

00:15:38.610 --> 00:15:41.990
President Abraham Lincoln issued
the Emancipation Proclamation

00:15:41.990 --> 00:15:47.160
on January 1, 1863 as, "A
fit and necessary war measure

00:15:47.160 --> 00:15:50.130
for suppressing said rebellion."

00:15:50.130 --> 00:15:52.820
In that fit and necessary
war measure,

00:15:52.820 --> 00:15:57.000
President Lincoln declared forever
free all persons held as slaves

00:15:57.000 --> 00:16:01.840
in the 10 states that were
at war with the United States

00:16:01.840 --> 00:16:04.510
for the independence
on January 1, 1863.

00:16:04.510 --> 00:16:08.710
And the five still holding states
that did not Abraham Lincoln as --

00:16:08.710 --> 00:16:10.890
that accepted Abraham
Lincoln as president;

00:16:10.890 --> 00:16:13.030
the Emancipation Proclamation
did not apply.

00:16:13.030 --> 00:16:15.440
It only applied to the states
that had to be brought back

00:16:15.440 --> 00:16:18.560 position:56%
into the Union by military conquest.

00:16:18.560 --> 00:16:20.850
On September 22, 1982,

00:16:20.850 --> 00:16:23.080
in the preliminary
Emancipation Proclamation,

00:16:23.080 --> 00:16:27.090
Lincoln warned the rebellious
states, giving them 100 days

00:16:27.090 --> 00:16:31.630
to return to the Union or he was
going to declare free their slaves.

00:16:31.630 --> 00:16:35.810 position:56%
Frederick Douglas, eight days later,
wrote in his monthly that in order

00:16:35.810 --> 00:16:38.680
for the Emancipation
Proclamation to free any slaves,

00:16:38.680 --> 00:16:40.830
two conditions had to be met.

00:16:40.830 --> 00:16:44.020
The first condition was that the
states in rebellion still had to be

00:16:44.020 --> 00:16:47.290
in rebellion as of January 1, 1863.

00:16:47.290 --> 00:16:51.950
And the second condition was,
"We must have the ability

00:16:51.950 --> 00:16:53.440
to put down the rebellion."

00:16:53.440 --> 00:17:03.360
In late 1862, the enslaved
knew that an order to be freed

00:17:03.360 --> 00:17:07.010
by the Emancipation Proclamation,
they would have to contribute

00:17:07.010 --> 00:17:11.360
to suppressing the rebellion
thus to preserving the Union.

00:17:11.360 --> 00:17:15.590
And this would have to be done
through military conquest.

00:17:15.590 --> 00:17:21.510
Thus begun -- thus began
their military campaign

00:17:21.510 --> 00:17:24.410
for emancipation and union.

00:17:24.410 --> 00:17:32.060 position:56%
It was understood by many members of
Congress, the President's Cabinet,

00:17:32.060 --> 00:17:34.900
the Confederate Legislature
and Jefferson Davis,

00:17:34.900 --> 00:17:36.200
the President of the Confederacy,

00:17:36.200 --> 00:17:39.760
that the Emancipation
Proclamation was a cry for help

00:17:39.760 --> 00:17:42.280
to America's African-descent
population.

00:17:42.280 --> 00:17:45.360
Jefferson Davis told the
Confederation Legislature

00:17:45.360 --> 00:17:50.410
in January 1863 that the
Emancipation Proclamation was,

00:17:50.410 --> 00:17:54.170
"An authentic statement by the
government of the United States

00:17:54.170 --> 00:17:57.910
of its inability to subjugate
the south by force of arms."

00:17:57.910 --> 00:18:07.210
Meanwhile in Texas, there is clear
evidence that enslaved persons

00:18:07.210 --> 00:18:08.910
in Galveston knew

00:18:08.910 --> 00:18:13.230
of the Emancipation
Proclamation in late 1862.

00:18:13.230 --> 00:18:18.210
Galveston was captured the
Union Navy in October 1862 --

00:18:18.210 --> 00:18:23.730
a navy comprised of 25%
African-American sailors.

00:18:23.730 --> 00:18:26.810
The Austrian Council at
Galveston wrote a letter

00:18:26.810 --> 00:18:33.030
to the Union Naval Commander,
Admiral William Renshaw,

00:18:33.030 --> 00:18:36.690
stating that Texas
slaves had run away

00:18:36.690 --> 00:18:40.480
and been given refuge
by Renshaw's fleet.

00:18:40.480 --> 00:18:45.720
The Council wanted to know
if his slaves ran away,

00:18:45.720 --> 00:18:47.720
would the Admiral return them?

00:18:47.720 --> 00:18:51.960
Renshaw unequivocally said, "No."

00:18:51.960 --> 00:18:56.940
Only a small army force, the 42nd
Massachusetts Infantry was assigned

00:18:56.940 --> 00:19:01.800
to occupied Galveston and the
rebels recaptured Galveston

00:19:01.800 --> 00:19:05.010
on the day the final Emancipation
Proclamation was issued,

00:19:05.010 --> 00:19:08.230
January 1, 1863.

00:19:08.230 --> 00:19:11.520
Union soldiers and sailors
were taken as prisoners of war

00:19:11.520 --> 00:19:16.850
and these Union soldiers
and sailors with knowledge

00:19:16.850 --> 00:19:20.090
of the Emancipation
Proclamation reported contact

00:19:20.090 --> 00:19:26.510
with enslaved Texans as some were
assigned to the POWs as cooks.

00:19:26.510 --> 00:19:30.200
The Union strategic plan
neglected military operations

00:19:30.200 --> 00:19:35.780
in Texas through much of 1863.

00:19:35.780 --> 00:19:39.320
Lincoln's priority in the west was

00:19:39.320 --> 00:19:42.290
on controlling the
Mississippi River.

00:19:42.290 --> 00:19:45.530
And Lincoln believed that the
only way the Mississippi could be

00:19:45.530 --> 00:19:51.650
controlled is with the help of
the African descent population.

00:19:51.650 --> 00:19:56.630 position:56%
When General Nathaniel Banks started
a Texas expedition along the Red

00:19:56.630 --> 00:20:00.730
River, he was ordered back
to the Mississippi in support

00:20:00.730 --> 00:20:04.740
of General Ulysses Grant's
campaign against Vicksburg.

00:20:04.740 --> 00:20:06.310
The Louisiana Native Guards,

00:20:06.310 --> 00:20:10.450
the first African descent regimen
mustered into the Union Army

00:20:10.450 --> 00:20:14.060
under the field command of African
descent commissioned officers led

00:20:14.060 --> 00:20:18.410
by Captain Andre [Inaudible]
assaulted the rebel position

00:20:18.410 --> 00:20:25.590 position:56%
at Port Hudson along the Mississippi
three times on May 27, 1863.

00:20:25.590 --> 00:20:31.400
Though these sable soldiers
failed to capture the rebel fort,

00:20:31.400 --> 00:20:35.390
they were successful in keeping
the rebels at Port Hudson

00:20:35.390 --> 00:20:38.740
from reinforcing the
rebels at Vicksburg.

00:20:38.740 --> 00:20:42.920
Therefore they had accomplished
their primary objective.

00:20:42.920 --> 00:20:46.860
Grant captured Vicksburg
on July 4, 1863.

00:20:46.860 --> 00:20:50.120
Now Lincoln had called
Vicksburg the key to victory.

00:20:50.120 --> 00:20:52.830
And after capturing Vicksburg,
Grant wrote to President Lincoln

00:20:52.830 --> 00:20:54.130
and told President Lincoln

00:20:54.130 --> 00:20:55.890
that Vicksburg could not have
been captured when it was

00:20:55.890 --> 00:20:58.460
without the help of these
African-American soldiers.

00:20:58.460 --> 00:21:03.480
The general goes on to tell the
President, "By arming the Negro,

00:21:03.480 --> 00:21:07.370
we have added a powerful ally."

00:21:07.370 --> 00:21:10.580
Such powerful allies
would participate

00:21:10.580 --> 00:21:14.680
in General Banks' Texas
expedition in November 1863.

00:21:14.680 --> 00:21:18.210
Rebel blockade runners
were able to bring supplies

00:21:18.210 --> 00:21:22.170
into Texas along Texas'
southernmost coast.

00:21:22.170 --> 00:21:28.480
And Banks was ordered to take
that part of the Texas coast.

00:21:28.480 --> 00:21:29.910
Five [inaudible] regiments --

00:21:29.910 --> 00:21:33.420
regiments comprised of
African-American soldiers

00:21:33.420 --> 00:21:40.490
from Louisiana took part in Banks'
successful Texas expedition making

00:21:40.490 --> 00:21:43.990
up 10% of the conquering force --

00:21:43.990 --> 00:21:47.070
capturing and conquering
the Texas Gulf coast

00:21:47.070 --> 00:21:49.770
from Indianola to Brownsville.

00:21:49.770 --> 00:21:52.710
These conquering soldiers
brought word

00:21:52.710 --> 00:21:56.330
of the Emancipation
Proclamation to Texas.

00:21:56.330 --> 00:21:59.320
John Bates was 10 years old

00:21:59.320 --> 00:22:03.270
when these military operations
were going on in Texas.

00:22:03.270 --> 00:22:07.960
Bates pointed out in his WPA
slave narrative that word,

00:22:07.960 --> 00:22:13.310
"traveled purty fast," and
that's P-U-R-T-Y [laughter] --

00:22:13.310 --> 00:22:18.140 position:56%
traveled pretty fast in Limestone
County, Texas where he was enslaved.

00:22:18.140 --> 00:22:21.150
Indeed Bates goes on to report
that it was the enslaved

00:22:21.150 --> 00:22:22.820
on the plantation where he was

00:22:22.820 --> 00:22:27.330
that told the planter
that they were free.

00:22:29.310 --> 00:22:33.100
The first state in
rebellion to be brought back

00:22:33.100 --> 00:22:36.480
in the Union thus having
its enslaves free --

00:22:36.480 --> 00:22:41.650
enslaved free by the Emancipation
Proclamation was Arkansas.

00:22:41.650 --> 00:22:44.120
It took one year and four months

00:22:44.120 --> 00:22:47.250
to enforce the Emancipation
Proclamation in a rebellious state

00:22:47.250 --> 00:22:53.730
and that state was not Virginia
with its proximity to Washington.

00:22:53.730 --> 00:22:59.740
That state was the western state
of Arkansas bordering Texas.

00:22:59.740 --> 00:23:02.940
When Arkansas was brought back
into the Union as a free state

00:23:02.940 --> 00:23:07.090
on April 11, 1864 there
were thousands

00:23:07.090 --> 00:23:11.300
of African descent soldiers
enforcing the Emancipation

00:23:11.300 --> 00:23:14.400
Proclamation in Arkansas.

00:23:14.400 --> 00:23:19.500
Meanwhile back in the East, in
1864, African descent soldiers

00:23:19.500 --> 00:23:22.680
for the first time were deployed
in the Army of the Potomac

00:23:22.680 --> 00:23:25.810
after General Grant became
the general in charge

00:23:25.810 --> 00:23:28.030
in command of all the armies.

00:23:28.030 --> 00:23:31.790
In December 1864, General
Benjamin F. Butler,

00:23:31.790 --> 00:23:33.950
the commander of the
Department of Virginia

00:23:33.950 --> 00:23:38.640 position:56%
and North Carolina organized the
25th Army Corps, the only Army Corps

00:23:38.640 --> 00:23:44.110
in American history made up of
only African descent regiments.

00:23:44.110 --> 00:23:47.930
Butler wrote of his
African descent soldiers,

00:23:47.930 --> 00:23:50.400
"Better soldiers never
shouldered a musket."

00:23:50.400 --> 00:23:56.960
General Grant wrote in his
memoirs that on April 3, 1865,

00:23:56.960 --> 00:23:58.680
the 25th Army Corps
under the command

00:23:58.680 --> 00:24:02.390
of General Godfrey Weitzel
captured Richmond, Virginia --

00:24:02.390 --> 00:24:05.170
the capital of the Confederacy.

00:24:06.770 --> 00:24:09.640
The headlines in the
Washington, DC newspaper,

00:24:09.640 --> 00:24:13.790
<i>The National Republican</i>
read, "Glorious Fall

00:24:13.790 --> 00:24:18.180
of Richmond Captured
by the Black Troops".

00:24:18.180 --> 00:24:22.830 position:56%
These sable soldiers of the 25th
went on to stop Robert E. Lee's army

00:24:22.830 --> 00:24:26.580
at Appomattox Court House,
Virginia forcing their surrender --

00:24:26.580 --> 00:24:30.880
his surrender there
on April 9, 1865.

00:24:30.880 --> 00:24:33.520
Though some contemporary
scholars falsely claimed

00:24:33.520 --> 00:24:37.980
that these highly regarded soldiers
were prohibited from participating

00:24:37.980 --> 00:24:41.890
in the grand review of the armies
in Washington on May 22nd --

00:24:41.890 --> 00:24:47.780
23rd and 24th, 1865
because of their race.

00:24:47.780 --> 00:24:53.210 position:56%
Without complaint, these highly
motivated sable soldiers stood ready

00:24:53.210 --> 00:24:56.850
to go to Texas and enforce
the Emancipation Proclamation

00:24:56.850 --> 00:24:59.030
in May of 1865.

00:24:59.030 --> 00:25:03.360
Thomas Morris Chester, an
African descent war correspondent,

00:25:03.360 --> 00:25:06.050
reported that on the
eve of the grand review,

00:25:06.050 --> 00:25:10.390
the word that they were
embarking for Texas was received

00:25:10.390 --> 00:25:15.190
in their camps, "With a
great deal of satisfaction."

00:25:15.190 --> 00:25:20.370
Out in Texas, African descent
soldiers who had been there

00:25:20.370 --> 00:25:26.730
for months engaged rebel
soldiers in combat in May of 1865.

00:25:26.730 --> 00:25:34.790
Galveston was captured and occupied
by the Union Navy on June 5, 1865.

00:25:34.790 --> 00:25:39.060
By the end of the first week
of June, the 25th Army Corps

00:25:39.060 --> 00:25:42.740
and thousands of other
reinforcements were arriving

00:25:42.740 --> 00:25:44.430
in the Lone Star State.

00:25:44.430 --> 00:25:50.750
In the early morning of June
15, 1865, the rebel governor

00:25:50.750 --> 00:25:54.890 position:56%
and thousands of rebel soldiers
were chased out of the United States

00:25:54.890 --> 00:26:00.320
into Mexico by this
imposing Union force.

00:26:00.320 --> 00:26:06.480 position:56%
The tradition of the Juneteenth Ball
on June 16th was thus established.

00:26:06.480 --> 00:26:10.010
General Gordon Granger
was the commander

00:26:10.010 --> 00:26:12.540
of the New Department of Texas.

00:26:12.540 --> 00:26:16.500
His immediate superior, General
Phil Sheridan, ordered Granger

00:26:16.500 --> 00:26:20.420
to publish general orders
informing the people of Texas

00:26:20.420 --> 00:26:24.890
that all the laws enacted by the
rebel governor and legislator --

00:26:24.890 --> 00:26:29.670
legislature were null and
void, that federal laws applied

00:26:29.670 --> 00:26:35.700
and thus the Emancipation
Proclamation had freed all the

00:26:35.700 --> 00:26:39.070
slaves in Texas forever.

00:26:39.070 --> 00:26:46.190
Granger arrived in Galveston on
June 19, 1865 and he reported

00:26:46.190 --> 00:26:51.270
to General Sheridan that
when he arrived that morning,

00:26:51.270 --> 00:26:58.000
there was a brigade of the 25th
Army Corps already in Galveston.

00:26:58.000 --> 00:27:05.630
Over a thousand African-American
soldiers, heroes of Virginia,

00:27:05.630 --> 00:27:12.550
were in Galveston over a week
before Granger showed up.

00:27:12.550 --> 00:27:16.720
Later that day, Granger published
General Order Number Three

00:27:16.720 --> 00:27:21.330
and the military campaign
for emancipation

00:27:21.330 --> 00:27:24.800
and union was officially
declared over.

00:27:24.800 --> 00:27:31.630
Let us therefore celebrate the
150th anniversary of the end

00:27:31.630 --> 00:27:36.960
of the successful campaign
for emancipation and union.

00:27:36.960 --> 00:27:42.780
On this Juneteenth, let us
embrace the truth, reject the lie,

00:27:42.780 --> 00:27:47.170
and pledge ourselves to achieving
liberty and justice for all

00:27:47.170 --> 00:27:50.690
in this our indivisible
American republic.

00:27:50.690 --> 00:27:52.490
Thank you.

00:27:52.490 --> 00:28:01.390
