00:38:48.370 --> 00:38:49.940
Our journey has been a long one.

00:38:49.940 --> 00:38:51.240
It's been a difficult one.

00:38:51.240 --> 00:38:53.040
But it's one that we chose.

00:38:53.040 --> 00:38:56.760
And with all the problems that
we've endured in terms of trying

00:38:56.760 --> 00:39:00.610
to build these institutions,
this is what we chose to do.

00:39:00.610 --> 00:39:05.370
This has been our job,
our task and our journey.

00:39:05.370 --> 00:39:10.170
My journey started actually in
Little Rock, Arkansas 73 years --

00:39:10.170 --> 00:39:13.860
I'm 73 years old -- 73 years ago.

00:39:13.860 --> 00:39:18.600 position:56%
With my mother, at that time, father
had escaped up towards Detroit,

00:39:18.600 --> 00:39:23.250
Michigan and as Juan
Killens would say.

00:39:23.250 --> 00:39:28.670
And then the journey somehow my
mother who is not with us now --

00:39:28.670 --> 00:39:32.970
in fact my mother -- this is
my memoir, <i>Yellow Black </i>.

00:39:32.970 --> 00:39:36.140
This is my mother here.

00:39:36.140 --> 00:39:41.420
You see, she's a very
beautiful woman.

00:39:41.420 --> 00:39:47.000
She was in the sex trade and by
the time she was 34, she was dead.

00:39:47.000 --> 00:39:52.660
But before that time, she
introduced me to literature.

00:39:52.660 --> 00:39:56.750
I write about it in <i>Yellow Black</i>
and I write that and I talk

00:39:56.750 --> 00:39:58.050
about libraries because
my mother introduced them.

00:39:58.050 --> 00:39:59.400
My introduction to the
library was the first place

00:39:59.400 --> 00:40:00.700
where I could -- I could hide.

00:40:00.700 --> 00:40:02.000
Libraries are free, brothers.

00:40:02.000 --> 00:40:03.800
It was kryptonite.

00:40:03.800 --> 00:40:06.640
An oxymoron to the 10th power.

00:40:06.640 --> 00:40:10.240
Libraries in Detroit in the
1950s were white, quiet,

00:40:10.240 --> 00:40:14.050
safe and sacred places with books,
ideas and white children trying

00:40:14.050 --> 00:40:16.210
to feed their minds and stay ahead.

00:40:16.210 --> 00:40:19.340
For me, the necessity of
libraries was early liberation

00:40:19.340 --> 00:40:22.010
to my young mind and soul.

00:40:22.010 --> 00:40:24.170
I devoured their content
like running oil

00:40:24.170 --> 00:40:26.830
in a bad engine of a used car.

00:40:26.830 --> 00:40:29.430
I was hot for knowledge
and the more I received,

00:40:29.430 --> 00:40:31.500
the greater I realized
the supreme ignorance

00:40:31.500 --> 00:40:34.330
of my ways and that of my family.

00:40:34.330 --> 00:40:37.470
For the first time, hope for
me appeared on the horizons

00:40:37.470 --> 00:40:39.400
with the acquisition
of my knowledge.

00:40:39.400 --> 00:40:41.450 position:56%
Defining the pure, practical answers

00:40:41.450 --> 00:40:44.450
that seldom entered the
black community propelled me

00:40:44.450 --> 00:40:48.260
into a long [inaudible]
that I would never leave.

00:40:48.260 --> 00:40:52.260 position:56%
To talk about ideas other than those
of the books, other than the work,

00:40:52.260 --> 00:40:56.270 position:56%
beating weakened women and money
placed me according to most brothers

00:40:56.270 --> 00:40:58.220
on another planet [laughter].

00:40:58.220 --> 00:41:00.660
It was like a musician discovered
the beauty and brilliance

00:41:00.660 --> 00:41:02.810
of Charlie Parker and
Dizzy Gillespie,

00:41:02.810 --> 00:41:05.890
realizing that their music
was genius and wondered

00:41:05.890 --> 00:41:08.310
if he could ever do that.

00:41:08.310 --> 00:41:12.640
The real task of getting the
young musicians to try books

00:41:12.640 --> 00:41:16.490
and music encouraged me to try.

00:41:16.490 --> 00:41:20.600
Maybe it was God and
[inaudible], our supreme judge

00:41:20.600 --> 00:41:23.630 position:56%
who instructed my mother to actually
go to the Detroit Public Library

00:41:23.630 --> 00:41:27.230
to check out <i>Black
Boy </i>by Richard Wright.

00:41:27.230 --> 00:41:31.480
I, at first, refused to go
because I did not want to go

00:41:31.480 --> 00:41:34.560
to a white library and ask a white
librarian for a book with black

00:41:34.560 --> 00:41:36.200 position:56%
in the title authored by a black man

00:41:36.200 --> 00:41:38.530
who I was told was challenging
white America's concept

00:41:38.530 --> 00:41:40.930
of itself and black people.

00:41:43.220 --> 00:41:45.540
Apartheid America had worked.

00:41:45.540 --> 00:41:50.860
I was completely ashamed of who
I was, felt inferior, inadequate

00:41:50.860 --> 00:41:54.300
and unprepared to answer the
simple question if asked,

00:41:54.300 --> 00:41:57.540
"Why do you want to
read <i>Black Boy </i>?"

00:41:57.540 --> 00:42:00.710
I found <i>Black Boy </i>with
luck on the library shelf.

00:42:00.710 --> 00:42:02.510
There were two copies.

00:42:02.510 --> 00:42:05.810
I took one of them, walked into
one side of the reading room

00:42:05.810 --> 00:42:09.280
and sat down and began to read.

00:42:09.280 --> 00:42:12.560
I was immediately captivated by
the boldness of the language,

00:42:12.560 --> 00:42:15.220
the clarity of the ideas, the
similarity of the [inaudible]

00:42:15.220 --> 00:42:17.070 position:56%
and living experience within my own.

00:42:17.070 --> 00:42:20.300
The familiarity of the
landscape, the intellectual genius

00:42:20.300 --> 00:42:25.090
of the protagonist to get what
he needed at any given time,

00:42:25.090 --> 00:42:28.200
the feeling of Richard
Wright to present a world

00:42:28.200 --> 00:42:36.060 position:56%
in which our people were completely
locked down emotionally, physically,

00:42:36.060 --> 00:42:37.360
economically and culturally --

00:42:37.360 --> 00:42:38.660
yet still functioning
as whole human beings.

00:42:38.660 --> 00:42:41.480
Which brings us most certainly
to what happened in Charleston.

00:42:41.480 --> 00:42:46.310
Whole human beings being shot
down by you know, white supremists

00:42:46.310 --> 00:42:49.050
and I know Miss Fenton spoke about
it this morning but I just wanted

00:42:49.050 --> 00:42:52.440
to again -- bring it back up that
our hearts go out to our brothers

00:42:52.440 --> 00:42:54.440
and sisters in Charleston.

00:42:54.440 --> 00:42:58.560
But as I read each word,
each sentence of paragraph

00:42:58.560 --> 00:42:59.860
after paragraph, page after page,

00:42:59.860 --> 00:43:03.590
it was like a sledgehammer
hitting me upside my head,

00:43:03.590 --> 00:43:07.840
stating in no uncertain
terms, "Wake up, Negro!"

00:43:07.840 --> 00:43:09.650
I checked out <i>Black Boy </i>.

00:43:09.650 --> 00:43:14.460
Ran home, went to the room I shared
with my sister and read all night.

00:43:14.460 --> 00:43:16.860
The next morning upon
completion of the book,

00:43:16.860 --> 00:43:20.900
the first serious book I
read in less than 24 hours,

00:43:20.900 --> 00:43:24.290
I was not a different person
but a different questioner.

00:43:24.290 --> 00:43:30.300
Wright gave me content, a long
content as I was beginning to move

00:43:30.300 --> 00:43:36.300
to the age of 14 and now
they focused on direction

00:43:36.300 --> 00:43:39.180
for my own culture and
intellectual development.

00:43:39.180 --> 00:43:49.720
His words formed the circle in our
own investigation into the ways

00:43:49.720 --> 00:43:51.020
and whys of white folks and my own.

00:43:51.020 --> 00:43:52.320
Life suddenly, suddenly it
slapped me right in the face.

00:43:52.320 --> 00:43:57.910
Read the white books,
newspapers, magazines and journals

00:43:57.910 --> 00:44:01.310
and [inaudible] and questioning
what was read is fundamental

00:44:01.310 --> 00:44:04.650
to developing a quicker
consciousness and world view.

00:44:04.650 --> 00:44:08.440
Knowledge of oneself, of
one's culture shapes a person.

00:44:08.440 --> 00:44:13.060
I do not know how my mother felt
about the literature she read.

00:44:13.060 --> 00:44:15.540
We never talked about it.

00:44:15.540 --> 00:44:19.040
All I remember is that she
once wanted me to read.

00:44:19.040 --> 00:44:23.880 position:56%
She was never angered by my spending
countless hours in the library.

00:44:23.880 --> 00:44:27.960
As our lives slowly slipped into
another world, mine did too.

00:44:27.960 --> 00:44:32.780 position:56%
Into the pavement of countless of
books that put me into other worlds,

00:44:32.780 --> 00:44:35.370
cultures, places and
without me knowing it,

00:44:35.370 --> 00:44:38.380
helped to determine my future.

00:44:38.380 --> 00:44:41.980
Black music had freed me creatively
and black literature began

00:44:41.980 --> 00:44:45.350
to find [inaudible] me
intellectually and culturally.

00:44:45.350 --> 00:44:47.350 position:56%
For the first time in my young life,

00:44:47.350 --> 00:44:50.030
I realized that life
has greater meaning

00:44:50.030 --> 00:44:51.870
than my personal circumstances.

00:44:51.870 --> 00:44:55.550
And I began to chance a smile
in between books, concepts

00:44:55.550 --> 00:44:59.100
and what I perceived was a
fine girl interested in me.

00:44:59.100 --> 00:45:01.820
I also picked up a pen and
began to write my own thoughts.

00:45:01.820 --> 00:45:08.480
I didn't call my words poetry but
became like square in a 12-round --

00:45:08.480 --> 00:45:11.070
sweat in a 12-round fight that
you didn't know you could win.

00:45:11.070 --> 00:45:14.530
Over proper training, there
was always a possibility

00:45:14.530 --> 00:45:20.530
of gaining ground if only a
yard, a word, a round at a time.

00:45:21.820 --> 00:45:27.140
You know, there's more but this
whole question of literature

00:45:27.140 --> 00:45:30.600
and reading, it is
absolutely necessary.

00:45:30.600 --> 00:45:35.760
For the last 75 days, I've been
getting up every morning at 4:30

00:45:35.760 --> 00:45:41.040
in the morning to write this book
which will be published in August.

00:45:41.040 --> 00:45:47.220
The title of the book is
"Taking Bullets" -- black men --

00:45:47.220 --> 00:45:50.390
black boys and men in 21st
century America fighting terrorism

00:45:50.390 --> 00:45:53.280
and violence and seeking
human space.

00:45:53.280 --> 00:45:57.310
And what set me on
this task and many

00:45:57.310 --> 00:45:59.410
of you may know I've written
two other books on black men.

00:45:59.410 --> 00:46:01.460
<i>Black Men: Obsolete,
Single, Dangerous </i>,

00:46:01.460 --> 00:46:05.470
African-American family
transitioning <i>Tough Notes:</i>

00:46:05.470 --> 00:46:07.400
<i>A Healing Call for Creating
Exceptional Black Men </i>.

00:46:07.400 --> 00:46:10.750
That my life has revolved
around black people.

00:46:10.750 --> 00:46:14.530
My wife and I spend over 90% of
our time in the black community.

00:46:14.530 --> 00:46:17.790
And I've had all -- you know,
I've taught at research one

00:46:17.790 --> 00:46:20.260
in universities, in urban
universities for the last --

00:46:20.260 --> 00:46:23.110
I'm retired now, for
the last 22 years.

00:46:23.110 --> 00:46:26.000
But the point is that our
community needs so much --

00:46:30.040 --> 00:46:31.340
-- and needs so much.

00:46:31.340 --> 00:46:33.640
&gt;&gt; Oh yes, yes.

00:46:33.640 --> 00:46:34.940
So much.

00:46:34.940 --> 00:46:36.240
&gt;&gt; Haki Madhubuti:
And the great majority

00:46:36.240 --> 00:46:40.290 position:56%
of our people do not know it, do not
understand what we are dealing with.

00:46:40.290 --> 00:46:42.610 position:56%
You know, we're dealing with empire.

00:46:42.610 --> 00:46:44.820
The United States is
the last empire.

00:46:44.820 --> 00:46:46.120
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:46:46.120 --> 00:46:47.420
&gt;&gt; Haki Madhubuti:
And these brothers are

00:46:47.420 --> 00:46:49.010
in these family corners,
you know, talking, "Mac,

00:46:49.010 --> 00:46:50.470
you know, this is my turf.

00:46:50.470 --> 00:46:51.770
They paying rent."

00:46:51.770 --> 00:46:53.070
&gt;&gt; Yes.

00:46:53.070 --> 00:46:54.370
&gt;&gt; Haki Madhubuti: They
don't own it, you know.

00:46:54.370 --> 00:46:56.310
I've lived here for
eight years in DC.

00:46:56.310 --> 00:47:03.410
Commuted every week
between Chicago and DC

00:47:03.410 --> 00:47:07.450
and I don't even know
this place anymore.

00:47:07.450 --> 00:47:08.750
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:47:08.750 --> 00:47:10.050
&gt;&gt; Haki Madhubuti:
And we don't know it.

00:47:10.050 --> 00:47:11.350
&gt; That's true.

00:47:11.350 --> 00:47:12.650
&gt;&gt; Haki Madhubuti: And if such
a question to ask, "Who are you?

00:47:12.650 --> 00:47:13.950
Who are you?"

00:47:13.950 --> 00:47:16.280
You ask 10 black people out on
the streets, "What's your name?

00:47:16.280 --> 00:47:17.590
Who are you?

00:47:17.590 --> 00:47:19.270
Where'd you come from?"

00:47:19.270 --> 00:47:22.860
You will get 10 different answers.

00:47:22.860 --> 00:47:28.470
In fact sometimes,
20 different answers.

00:47:28.470 --> 00:47:29.770
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:47:29.770 --> 00:47:31.070 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Haki Madhubuti: If you don't know
who you are, anybody can name you.

00:47:31.070 --> 00:47:32.370
And they will.

00:47:32.370 --> 00:47:33.670
And so we find ourselves
in this continued war,

00:47:33.670 --> 00:47:34.970
this continued pattern to just
to be human, just to be human.

00:47:34.970 --> 00:47:36.270
Black people don't have
no place else to go.

00:47:36.270 --> 00:47:37.570
And you know, these clowns
are like, "Go back to Africa."

00:47:37.570 --> 00:47:38.870
What?

00:47:38.870 --> 00:47:40.170
[ Laughter ]

00:47:40.170 --> 00:47:41.470
You talking about Africa,
Mississippi?

00:47:41.470 --> 00:47:44.640
You know, Arkansas?

00:47:44.640 --> 00:47:50.120
And so for us, my wife and I
and -- and trying to create,

00:47:50.120 --> 00:47:53.030
we need independent
black institutions.

00:47:53.030 --> 00:47:56.360
Not Negro institutions, not
imitation white institutions.

00:47:56.360 --> 00:47:58.140
We need institutions that
are essentially going to talk

00:47:58.140 --> 00:48:00.450
about us, to give us direction.

00:48:02.070 --> 00:48:03.370
We need family.

00:48:03.370 --> 00:48:05.240
We need community.

00:48:05.240 --> 00:48:07.940
And people say, "Well, why -- you
know why does black [inaudible]?"

00:48:07.940 --> 00:48:09.990
You know, black-on-black
crime exists

00:48:09.990 --> 00:48:11.720
because of white-on-black crime."

00:48:11.720 --> 00:48:13.020
&gt;&gt; They all do.

00:48:13.020 --> 00:48:14.320
&gt;&gt; Haki Madhubuti: What we
do, we've been taught to do.

00:48:14.320 --> 00:48:15.620
&gt;&gt; Yes.

00:48:15.620 --> 00:48:18.260
&gt;&gt; Haki Madhubuti: You see, women
taught to kill white people,

00:48:18.260 --> 00:48:21.600
not in [inaudible] -- the people
who raped us in another continent

00:48:21.600 --> 00:48:23.090
so we don't do that but
we kill black people

00:48:23.090 --> 00:48:26.160
because we devalued
black people's lives.

00:48:26.160 --> 00:48:28.300
You see, so we got a
lot of drive-by shooting

00:48:28.300 --> 00:48:30.990
but we got drive-by looters.

00:48:30.990 --> 00:48:36.670
The central problem in America is
white supremacy based upon white

00:48:36.670 --> 00:48:39.070
nationalism, you see.

00:48:39.070 --> 00:48:42.870
That has infiltrated itself
and lived within the context

00:48:42.870 --> 00:48:44.170
of these institutional structures

00:48:44.170 --> 00:48:45.870
and most certainly
the police structures

00:48:45.870 --> 00:48:49.130
in this country -- the
military and police.

00:48:49.130 --> 00:48:50.960
I've served three years
in the military.

00:48:50.960 --> 00:48:54.110
I understand what exactly
that meant there.

00:48:54.110 --> 00:48:57.930
And so, in trying to build these
independent black institutions

00:48:57.930 --> 00:49:02.600
