01:47:49.440 --> 01:47:53.920
But I was interested in the story
and stories of famous people

01:47:53.920 --> 01:47:57.850
and how historical figures
overcame obstacles, and mysteries,

01:47:57.850 --> 01:47:59.750
and friendships, and triumphs.

01:47:59.750 --> 01:48:04.390
I remember one book about a
little girl who faced racism

01:48:04.390 --> 01:48:07.900
and it's interesting that I can't
remember the name of that book,

01:48:07.900 --> 01:48:11.300
since that was the only one
I remember that depicted me.

01:48:11.300 --> 01:48:13.880
For some reason, I
blocked out the title.

01:48:13.880 --> 01:48:15.700
But books were my comfort,

01:48:15.700 --> 01:48:20.140
as my other colleagues have
said, my solace, my friends.

01:48:20.140 --> 01:48:23.720
Because they were a way
of reimagining my life.

01:48:23.720 --> 01:48:27.980
And when I became a parent,
instilling a love and --

01:48:27.980 --> 01:48:30.690
of reading and writing
was very paramount to me.

01:48:30.690 --> 01:48:34.120
I was determined that my
children would be reading

01:48:34.120 --> 01:48:35.920
and writing before
they entered school.

01:48:35.920 --> 01:48:38.440
In fact, I even thought
about homeschooling

01:48:38.440 --> 01:48:42.040
and opening my own school
because like so many people

01:48:42.040 --> 01:48:44.870
in my generation, I
was very disillusioned

01:48:44.870 --> 01:48:46.170
with the public school system.

01:48:46.170 --> 01:48:50.380
I had worked in a middle
school and elementary school

01:48:50.380 --> 01:48:54.200
and the students were
two years behind

01:48:54.200 --> 01:48:57.040
in their reading at both levels.

01:48:57.040 --> 01:49:01.530 position:56%
And I viewed this as a tragedy and
determined to do something about it.

01:49:01.530 --> 01:49:04.860
So the first thing I did was when
I worked on my Master's Degree,

01:49:04.860 --> 01:49:08.210
I decided to get it in
the teaching of reading.

01:49:08.210 --> 01:49:12.110
And I did my Doctoral Degree
in the teaching of writing,

01:49:12.110 --> 01:49:15.260
so that I could really
become proficient in that.

01:49:15.260 --> 01:49:20.370 position:56%
And one of the things that I've
learned over the years as a educator

01:49:20.370 --> 01:49:25.950
for over four decades, is that
children come to reading processes

01:49:25.950 --> 01:49:29.100
at different stages
and in different ways.

01:49:29.100 --> 01:49:31.340
Everyone has their own journey.

01:49:31.340 --> 01:49:37.640
And what you have to do is to
surround students with language,

01:49:37.640 --> 01:49:42.780
with read -- opportunities to read
and write to them as we all know.

01:49:42.780 --> 01:49:45.590
And there was a book
that had an impact on me.

01:49:45.590 --> 01:49:49.650
It was a woman named Glenda
Bissex, who did her dissertation

01:49:49.650 --> 01:49:52.420
on her student's growth
into literacy.

01:49:52.420 --> 01:49:53.720
It's called <i>Gnys at Wrk </i>.

01:49:53.720 --> 01:49:59.570
And she spelled genius
G-N-Y-S, <i>Gnys At Wrk </i>.

01:49:59.570 --> 01:50:08.240
She chronicled her son reading and
writing, and by the time he was

01:50:08.240 --> 01:50:13.970
in late primary school he was
writing newsletters for his school.

01:50:13.970 --> 01:50:17.930
And I was concerned
that, as an educator,

01:50:17.930 --> 01:50:23.210
my son should have been reading
early, because I had a master's

01:50:23.210 --> 01:50:26.710
in reading and was doing my
doctoral work in reading.

01:50:26.710 --> 01:50:30.460
But I realized that there are
different ways of reading.

01:50:30.460 --> 01:50:35.240
One other thing, my son is a
hip-hop artist, Talib Kweli.

01:50:35.240 --> 01:50:39.830
He began writing before
he was actually reading.

01:50:39.830 --> 01:50:45.240
He actually -- he loved telling
stories and he loved drawing.

01:50:45.240 --> 01:50:48.390
So he would draw these books.

01:50:48.390 --> 01:50:51.640
And he -- I would give him
reams of computer paper

01:50:51.640 --> 01:50:53.350
and he would draw these pictures.

01:50:53.350 --> 01:50:58.110
And then, he would put captions
on the bottom of the pictures.

01:50:58.110 --> 01:51:02.090 position:56%
And so, he was writing picture books
before he was actually reading.

01:51:02.090 --> 01:51:05.050
He was doing that reading we
talked about earlier, you know,

01:51:05.050 --> 01:51:07.350
my son can read, but they
had memorized the text.

01:51:07.350 --> 01:51:08.650
We all know that.

01:51:08.650 --> 01:51:10.570
You know, children go
through that, right?

01:51:10.570 --> 01:51:18.380
So he actually also had a
special journey into reading,

01:51:18.380 --> 01:51:21.580
and by the time he was
five years old, was writing

01:51:21.580 --> 01:51:26.800
and then producing shows about
books that he had written.

01:51:26.800 --> 01:51:29.770
Whenever there was a family
gathering he would take his --

01:51:29.770 --> 01:51:34.140
produce this show and get all
of his cousins together and put

01:51:34.140 --> 01:51:40.390 position:56%
on a production based on what he had
written and the characters he had.

01:51:40.390 --> 01:51:45.740
So my love of books and
reading really formed the seeds

01:51:45.740 --> 01:51:51.070
of literary activism, which
always attribute that to my friend

01:51:51.070 --> 01:51:54.260
and colleague, E. Ethelbert
Miller, who calls --

01:51:54.260 --> 01:51:56.450
said, "I'm a literary activist."

01:51:56.450 --> 01:51:58.000
I also am a literary activist.

01:51:58.000 --> 01:51:59.450
And when I was student teaching,

01:51:59.450 --> 01:52:03.660
I worked in an alternative
school with reluctant readers.

01:52:03.660 --> 01:52:09.440
And one young man who was reading
years below on the school level,

01:52:09.440 --> 01:52:13.240
never writing, I said,
"Well, I'm going to make sure

01:52:13.240 --> 01:52:16.360
and get you -- motivate
you to write."

01:52:16.360 --> 01:52:18.320
And so, he loved music.

01:52:18.320 --> 01:52:20.140
He played the guitar.

01:52:20.140 --> 01:52:22.610
So we went to a guitar
store and he got --

01:52:22.610 --> 01:52:24.870
I got him to buy books

01:52:24.870 --> 01:52:27.940
that represented lyrics
of songs he wrote.

01:52:27.940 --> 01:52:31.070
And then, he would come
back and that was his way.

01:52:31.070 --> 01:52:36.350
By the time the program
was over, he was writing.

01:52:36.350 --> 01:52:41.770
In my work as executive director
of the Center for Black Literature,

01:52:41.770 --> 01:52:44.710
we have a program called
Re-Envisioning Our Lives

01:52:44.710 --> 01:52:46.010
Through Literature.

01:52:46.010 --> 01:52:48.250
We go into the public schools --

01:52:48.250 --> 01:52:51.720
we bring teaching artists into the
public schools, in middle schools

01:52:51.720 --> 01:52:54.500
and high schools, sometimes
elementary schools.

01:52:54.500 --> 01:52:57.150
And we work with students
on creating --

01:52:57.150 --> 01:52:59.980
giving them opportunities
to create stories,

01:52:59.980 --> 01:53:04.700
to create poetry, to create skits.

01:53:04.700 --> 01:53:06.290
They create and anthology.

01:53:06.290 --> 01:53:09.140
In fact, I have one here
that they just finished

01:53:09.140 --> 01:53:11.640
and it's based on "Roll Call."

01:53:11.640 --> 01:53:14.210
When we give them a
book, and we used --

01:53:14.210 --> 01:53:16.330
we've been using "Roll Call"
for the last few years.

01:53:16.330 --> 01:53:18.400
Hakeem Abuhti, [phonetic] mentioned

01:53:18.400 --> 01:53:22.550
"Roll Call" that's
published by Third Row Press.

01:53:22.550 --> 01:53:25.870
And so, we give them Roll Call
and they read the stories,

01:53:25.870 --> 01:53:28.680
and then they take those
stories and use it as the basis

01:53:28.680 --> 01:53:31.540
to create their own
stories and literary text.

01:53:31.540 --> 01:53:37.730
And I just want to read to you one
of the stories, one of the letters

01:53:37.730 --> 01:53:40.530
that came out of that,
just a part of it.

01:53:40.530 --> 01:53:41.830
This is by Yassim [phonetic].

01:53:41.830 --> 01:53:44.560
it's called "The Struggle."

01:53:44.560 --> 01:53:48.100
"I stare at the empty black
hole that is my future

01:53:48.100 --> 01:53:50.640
and the bright light
that is my past.

01:53:50.640 --> 01:53:54.040
I examine the struggle
that my brother, mother,

01:53:54.040 --> 01:53:56.950
sisters, ancestors have survived.

01:53:56.950 --> 01:54:00.770
What was the purpose, what
did we do to deserve this?

01:54:00.770 --> 01:54:02.290
Red fills my eyes.

01:54:02.290 --> 01:54:06.650 position:56%
I can hear the blood pumping through
my veins as my pulse quickens.

01:54:06.650 --> 01:54:08.480
I can hear the screams
and the yells.

01:54:08.480 --> 01:54:11.650
I can feel the wipes and the cotton
thorns as they prick my skin.

01:54:11.650 --> 01:54:13.710
I read the White Only signs.

01:54:13.710 --> 01:54:16.870
And I feel the desperation
as a man runs from the house,

01:54:16.870 --> 01:54:18.450
a girl cries, a woman dies.

01:54:18.450 --> 01:54:19.750
It's over.

01:54:19.750 --> 01:54:21.460
Is this it, was that all?

01:54:21.460 --> 01:54:24.260
Is this what my ancestors
have survived,

01:54:24.260 --> 01:54:26.510
have fought against
for me to be here?

01:54:26.510 --> 01:54:29.610
As I witness the brutality
of the past, as time goes on,

01:54:29.610 --> 01:54:31.680
I see my future brighten.

01:54:31.680 --> 01:54:35.560
I shall stand strong, for this
is what my people have struggled

01:54:35.560 --> 01:54:37.890
through, what I may
struggle through.

01:54:37.890 --> 01:54:43.130
But that's okay, I can turn around
and walk towards my bright future."

01:54:43.130 --> 01:54:46.520
And that's an example of
the kind of work that we get

01:54:46.520 --> 01:54:49.910
from our young people when
we give them opportunities

01:54:49.910 --> 01:54:52.490
to use their imagination
in the schools

01:54:52.490 --> 01:54:54.220
and give them some
real text to read.

01:54:54.220 --> 01:54:57.030
We ask -- we give them the book.

01:54:57.030 --> 01:54:59.510
They're not just reading
little passages;

01:54:59.510 --> 01:55:03.980
we're trying to make reading
very meaningful to them.

01:55:03.980 --> 01:55:08.190
So, that's Re-Envisioning
Our Lives Through Literature.

01:55:08.190 --> 01:55:13.200
One of the things that
Talib says to me is

01:55:13.200 --> 01:55:17.660
that you can't just
give people the words.

01:55:17.660 --> 01:55:19.010
You have to give them a hook.

01:55:19.010 --> 01:55:20.530 position:56%
If you want them to get the message,

01:55:20.530 --> 01:55:23.770
you have to find out
what the hook is.

01:55:23.770 --> 01:55:28.290 position:56%
And I think one of the main
challenges that we face as educators

01:55:28.290 --> 01:55:34.400
and as parents is how do we find
a hook for our young people?

01:55:34.400 --> 01:55:38.520
How do we find creative ways for
them to get hooked into language

01:55:38.520 --> 01:55:39.940
and to writing and reading?

01:55:39.940 --> 01:55:42.130
We have to create those spaces,

01:55:42.130 --> 01:55:46.070
and they have to be
intentional and deliberate.

01:55:46.070 --> 01:55:49.250
And when we look at the impact
of the internet and social media

01:55:49.250 --> 01:55:52.780
and popular culture, the decline
in independent black book stores,

01:55:52.780 --> 01:55:56.920
the merger of publishing companies,
the disappearance of sections

01:55:56.920 --> 01:56:00.670
in bookstores devoted
to black writers,

01:56:00.670 --> 01:56:03.290
we understand what
those challenges are.

01:56:03.290 --> 01:56:06.540
Our students are reading and
writing in different ways,

01:56:06.540 --> 01:56:10.410
and we cannot ignore the
21st century technology.

01:56:10.410 --> 01:56:13.230
Have you witnessed those students,
who, when they read the poem,

01:56:13.230 --> 01:56:15.030
they come up with their iPad?

01:56:15.030 --> 01:56:17.150
They're reading from their iPads.

01:56:17.150 --> 01:56:19.460
Right. You know, they're
not reading from the text.

01:56:19.460 --> 01:56:21.440
So we have to find a
way to draw on that.

01:56:21.440 --> 01:56:24.600
I mean, how often do you
see a young person sitting

01:56:24.600 --> 01:56:27.000
down and reading a book?

01:56:27.000 --> 01:56:30.360 position:56%
And look at what's happened, at
least in Brooklyn, in the libraries.

01:56:30.360 --> 01:56:32.500
The libraries are full with
young people in the afternoon,

01:56:32.500 --> 01:56:35.910
and that's because there's no
other place for them to go.

01:56:35.910 --> 01:56:37.210
They go to the library.

01:56:37.210 --> 01:56:38.570
It becomes a place
where they can hang out.

01:56:38.570 --> 01:56:42.330 position:56%
They're not necessarily reading, but
we can draw on that and capitalize

01:56:42.330 --> 01:56:44.310
on that to create a space

01:56:44.310 --> 01:56:47.420
to get them more involved
in reading and writing.

01:56:47.420 --> 01:56:50.670
Which means we have to
support the libraries more,

01:56:50.670 --> 01:56:52.450
they have to be funded more.

01:56:52.450 --> 01:56:54.420
We have to demand that.

01:56:54.420 --> 01:56:59.310
When we look at reading behaviors,
someone mentioned the third grade.

01:56:59.310 --> 01:57:03.370
The third grade becomes that first
step when you lose the readers,

01:57:03.370 --> 01:57:05.050
and then it's the sixth grade.

01:57:05.050 --> 01:57:08.580
There's a correlation between
students' reading behaviors

01:57:08.580 --> 01:57:12.480
in sixth grade and then
what happens later on?

01:57:12.480 --> 01:57:16.510
So we have to -- we have
some formidable challenges,

01:57:16.510 --> 01:57:18.490
we have to make the
literature produced

01:57:18.490 --> 01:57:21.800
by writers throughout the
African diaspora more available

01:57:21.800 --> 01:57:24.350
in our schools and for
the general public.

01:57:24.350 --> 01:57:26.140
Which means we have to make sure

01:57:26.140 --> 01:57:30.510
that we get librarians
to order those books.

01:57:30.510 --> 01:57:34.330
And in our schools, we have
to make sure that they're part

01:57:34.330 --> 01:57:37.050
of that cannon, which is
one of the things we do

01:57:37.050 --> 01:57:39.490
