of paper or on a book,
see what it said,

03:01:11.360 --> 03:01:15.000
let alone write it for yourself.

03:01:18.570 --> 03:01:27.550
Somehow or the other we have got
to be able to convey that sense

03:01:27.550 --> 03:01:30.610
that the slaves understood
inherently of what it meant

03:01:30.610 --> 03:01:36.430
to be free to our children
and our young people.

03:01:36.430 --> 03:01:45.000
The most tragic deficiency a child
can have is the inability to read.

03:01:48.990 --> 03:01:58.000
Even if somehow she can't speak,
if she can read she's on her way.

03:02:01.760 --> 03:02:08.560
So for us and for the
African American community,

03:02:08.560 --> 03:02:15.000
reading is as much a priority
today as it was 150 years ago.

03:02:21.210 --> 03:02:25.760
In a real sense if it
was seen as the key

03:02:25.760 --> 03:02:35.450
to freedom then it is obviously
essential to freedom today.

03:02:35.450 --> 03:02:40.870
When reading and writing is
not enough, when appreciation

03:02:40.870 --> 03:02:42.550
for literature, for culture,

03:02:42.550 --> 03:02:46.970
for the world in which
you live is now required.

03:02:46.970 --> 03:02:54.110
But you can't do that if
you can't read and write.

03:02:54.110 --> 03:02:59.770
So how to inspire our young
people, how to use our history.

03:02:59.770 --> 03:03:02.250
That is worth.

03:03:02.250 --> 03:03:08.860
Laid out for us to inspire our
own young people to learn to read

03:03:08.860 --> 03:03:13.830
and write in the very same
way that their forbearers did.

03:03:15.300 --> 03:03:22.250
In this city we are especially
inspired by Juneteenth

03:03:23.990 --> 03:03:33.860 position:56%
because in this city the slaves were
liberated nine months before the

03:03:33.860 --> 03:03:36.450
<i>Emancipation Proclamation </i>.

03:03:36.450 --> 03:03:42.520
We were the first to be liberated.

03:03:42.520 --> 03:03:50.440
So on April 16th in the District
of Columbia that liberation is

03:03:50.440 --> 03:03:53.470
so important that it is a holiday
in the District of Columbia.

03:03:53.470 --> 03:03:56.640
Don't even go to work [laughter].

03:03:56.640 --> 03:03:58.680
That's how important it is.

03:03:58.680 --> 03:04:01.820
So there's a big parade downtown.

03:04:01.820 --> 03:04:03.950
That's our wig day when
everybody else is working.

03:04:03.950 --> 03:04:06.920
Well, we're walking in
the District of Columbia

03:04:06.920 --> 03:04:11.850 position:56%
because we understand how
important being free and free first.

03:04:11.850 --> 03:04:14.150
Oh, my goodness.

03:04:15.480 --> 03:04:21.370
My own great-grandfather, Richard
Holmes, was in the District

03:04:21.370 --> 03:04:26.320
of Columbia on that day that
the slaves in the District

03:04:26.320 --> 03:04:29.410
of Columbia became
the first to be freed.

03:04:29.410 --> 03:04:34.440
He was not a free man.

03:04:34.440 --> 03:04:37.610
He was a runaway slave.

03:04:37.610 --> 03:04:41.460
He walked away from a slave
plantation in Virginia

03:04:41.460 --> 03:04:44.180
and made his way to Washington.

03:04:44.180 --> 03:04:47.890
Now I don't tell any stories
on miss about Richard Holmes.

03:04:47.890 --> 03:04:54.420
He didn't gather himself together
a group of slaves and said,

03:04:54.420 --> 03:04:59.210
let's sneak away from the
master and look at the hour

03:04:59.210 --> 03:05:02.700
and then hear my call
and let's be gone.

03:05:04.300 --> 03:05:08.030
